u, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the 